<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ecommerce-sales-funnel-create-account-example.jpg" alt="&quot;Create Account&quot; example" width="694" height="181" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p class="text-align-center"><a href="https://www.shopify.com/blog/customer-retention-strategies#account" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Image Source</em></a></p>
<h3>2. Implement upsells, cross-sells, and add ons</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/11/12/is-email-marketing-effective">Effective email marketing</a> is about continuing the conversation between your company and your customer. Itâ€™s a highly viable digital marketing strategy. In fact, nearly <a href="https://blog.hubspot.com/marketing/email-marketing-stats" target="_blank" rel="noopener">60%</a> of marketers say email marketing is their biggest source of ROI.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="1684fb0d-8634-4b62-8a87-e3b0274994a6" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ecommerce-sales-funnel-upsell-crossell-image.jpg" alt="upselll vs cross sell graphic" width="700" height="353" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>We like to use email marketing to offer upsells, cross-sells, and add ons.</p>
<p>What youâ€™re effectively doing is reaching out to customers who you know have an interest in your company and are making targeted and specific recommendations based on their previous transaction history.</p>
<p>You can send your customer an email for any reason, but we like itâ€™s relevant to the customerâ€™s personal journey with your product. For example, sending a customer a post-purchase email to offer add-ons to the core product they purchased is a great way to increase the average ticket order.</p>
<p><strong>But emails donâ€™t need to be sent immediately after an order is placed to have value</strong>.</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s a great example from Asana:</p>
